label chapter16:

    # [Scene: Loading Bay, Marisora Outskirts | Dawn]

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low diesel idling, gulls calling like distant alarms, the rustle of tarp]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft piano with rising strings — hopeful, steady]
    "You breathe in and the morning tastes of diesel and tomato leaves — a strange, grounding mix. The seed-bank crates sit open on the back of the truck, burlap and hand-lettered labels, the smell of peat"
    "and pepper seedlings curling up into the cold air. Your fingers know the weight of each packet: decades of saved varieties, the slow, stubborn history of people who refused to let the sea erase the whole"
    "of them."
    "You run your thumb along the brass rim of the tide-watch. It is warmer where your skin presses; the second hand is a patient small thing, marking steps you did not imagine you'd have to take."
    "Leaving had a political logic when you argued it at the meeting. Now it is a choreography of hands and vehicles and promises that must be kept until they are true."
    "Elias crouches by a crate, his hair flecked with soil and salt, jaw working as he ties rope. The light catches the sawdust on his sleeves like a constellation."
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "There — label facing out. Arlo, keep the dried-mango packs with the medicinal seeds. Rita, the saplings go last; they're the most delicate in transit."
    show elias_jun at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_jun "You always make it sound like a military operation.' (He smiles, but it doesn't touch his eyes yet.) 'Good. Whoever planned this didn't expect the kids to get sentimental about compost."

    maya_reyes "Sentimental about compost is exactly the profile we need for resilience."

    elias_jun "Right. Hard to mobilize people without a little biodegradability."
    show rita_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rita_ortega "We've got the manifests. Truck one goes upriver to the LaGuardia docks. Truck two is for the rooftop kits — pots, soil mix, the telescopes — because you insisted telescopes are non-negotiable."

    "Maya Reyes (there in the sound of Rita's voice is the town's continuity — a practical warmth)" "Thank you. Make sure the cold boxes are checked again. Nothing damp at all."

    rita_ortega "Checked twice. And Maya?' (Her tone softens.) 'You look like you're carrying the harbor on your back. Let someone else carry a corner, yeah?"
    "You pause, the sentence settling like a pebble in your chest. The ledger of responsibilities you kept to yourself is not, in practice, a private object. It is rostered across the shoulders of everyone here, and the weight shifts when you let it."

    maya_reyes "I'll carry the tide-watch."

    rita_ortega "As long as you don't try to navigate by it. We have a map for that."

    menu:
        "Tuck the tide-watch into your coat.":
            "You press the tide-watch into the inner pocket near your sternum. The metal cools again, but its tick becomes part of your breathing."
        "Leave the tide-watch on your wrist, exposed.":
            "The tide-watch becomes a small, visible anchor. People glance at it like a signal; Elias catches your eye and nods, as if the watch were a tiny flag."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue main narrative"
    "Elias moves to help you hoist a battered crate into the truck. He hums something without words, a beat that was part nursery-song, part dented engine. You both lift; your palms know the map of the wood, the grooves worn by other hands over other years."

    elias_jun "We will come back. We have Marisora in our bones, M —"

    "Maya Reyes (you let the unfinished thing sit; you are used to holding sentences loose so they won't break those around you)" "We will come back to what we can. We will rebuild what we must. We take the seeds, the stories, and the people who want to go. The rest will decide what they need."

    elias_jun "That sounds like a promise and a plan, which is better than either alone.' (He taps the crate as if it were a heart.) 'Write to me when the tide-line changes."

    maya_reyes "I'll send mangrove slips first thing from the rooftop greenhouse when we've set one up.' (You can feel the small labor of it already — seedlings wrapped in damp cloth, packed like secret letters.) 'And I'll call Mayor Tomas. Keep Rita's number close — she'll be the one making sure everyone's on the manifest."

    rita_ortega "And I'll be the one making sure no one tries to bury their stubbornness in the compost pile."
    "The vehicles roll, cargo shifting with the small, impatient sounds of life moving. You climb into the passenger seat of the lead truck, and for a long moment the town dissolves into frames in the window:"
    "the bakery's board empty now, the breakwater a ragged stitch, the harbor's shape in your mind like a carved bowl."
    # [Scene: Moving Highway, Salt Flats and Reedbeds | Midday]
    hide maya_reyes
    hide elias_jun
    hide rita_ortega

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Tires on wet asphalt, a radio murmuring municipal updates every so often]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low cello underpinning, strings lifting; the rhythm of travel]
    "You sleep in half-hour stitches, the kind of micro-sleep that comes in the hollow of exhaustion and adrenaline. When you wake, Elias is sketching plans on a scrap of waterproof paper — a modular aquaculture barge,"
    "simplified, a sketchalike promise. He makes little notes in the margins, hands moving with the authority of someone who builds with their palms."
    show elias_jun at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_jun "If we anchor the grow-frames with cross-tension, the upriver current will bring nutrients and pull away excess bloom. Less maintenance. More yield."
    "Maya Reyes: (you read the lines; your scientist's ribs rearrange to match his builder's intuition) 'We can model the nutrient flux, but we'll need a sensor array to monitor salinity daily. I can set up a simple loop — cheap sondes that ping to a hotspot.'"

    elias_jun "You talk expensive-sounding, and I'm into it."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "It's not expensive if we prioritize — and if we tag it as community infrastructure, we can tap the regional grant Ayla mentioned."

    elias_jun "Ayla helped pick the town, didn't she?"

    maya_reyes "She did. She negotiated the slots, smoothed the permits. We argued about timelines, but she got us the corridor."

    elias_jun "She still makes it sound like an equation."

    maya_reyes "She is an equation. You and I are the variables that make other people care about the numbers."
    "He looks at you, and there is a softness there, a gratitude braided with grief: gratitude for the plan, grief for what is left behind."
    # [Scene: New Coastal Town — LaGuardia Docks | Early Evening]
    hide elias_jun
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: River traffic, a bell from a market stand, distant laughter]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm strings, piano flourishes — an ascending motif]
    "The town smells different — less of kelp and more of river mud and young pine. The municipal liaison meets you with a clipboard and a smile that's almost shy after Marisora's pitched politics."

    "Municipal Liaison" "Welcome. We have a cluster of temporary rentals near the old mill. Rooftops available for gardens, and the youth center can host the greenhouse while permits finalize."
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Thank you. We'll need power runs for the sensor array and space for the seed bank. Can you tell me about local fishing communities? Their seasons?"

    "Municipal Liaison" "They're mixed. Some run small riverside nets; others are experimenting with oyster lines. You're not alone here."

    "Maya Reyes (a swallow of relief)" "Then we can trade techniques — mangrove slips for oyster-line know-how."
    "Elias Jun unloads a crate and the movement of his shoulders after a day on the road is the most beautiful practical thing you see. He sets the crate down and opens it with a care"
    "that is almost ritual. Inside: jars of seeds, labeled in Rita's hand, a small knitted bag of your grandmother's scarves, a battered tide-watch in its pocket."
    show elias_jun at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_jun "This is home-work, I can tell."

    maya_reyes "It's our work. It'll keep us up some nights. It'll keep us steady on others."

    menu:
        "Offer the telescope to the local youth center.":
            "The telescope becomes a bridge. Children crowd around the rooftop and the river feels smaller, mapped into orbits and bright points. Elias grins as a teenager aligns the lens, hands awkward and brave."
        "Keep the telescope for the rooftop garden observation.":
            "You mount the telescope above the potted herbs. It watches the stretch of river the way you once watched the harbor — a way to collect nights and measure distance with a deliberate gaze."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue main narrative"
    "Rita moves through the neighborhood like a bright, practical comet: arranging meeting times, shuffling names, negotiating the use of a community shed for the greenhouse panels. She finds you on a borrowed stoop and takes your hands in both of hers."
    show rita_ortega at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rita_ortega "You did it. For now — you did the thing that saved people with dignity. You're allowed to be tired and proud."

    maya_reyes "I keep waiting for a part of me to feel like I betrayed Marisora by leaving, and another part to feel like I did the only sane thing. Most of the time it's both at once."

    rita_ortega "That's okay. Humans are allowed to carry contradictions. It's how we make room for everything that matters."

    elias_jun "And here I was hoping contradictions would be simple enough to nail with screws."
    "You all laugh, a small, bright sound. It lands like sunlight on the new town's concrete."
    # [Scene: Temporary Greenhouse, Weeks Later | Afternoon]
    hide maya_reyes
    hide elias_jun
    hide rita_ortega

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Water trickling through a drip line, distant hammering]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Rising strings; notes of optimism]

    "You stand in the humidity with your palms damp and the smell of seedlings thick in your nose. Small plastic tags bob in soil like signposts" "Marisora — Heirloom Pepper,' 'Mangrove Slip — 2026,' 'Elias' Modular Frame Test."
    show elias_jun at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_jun "You were right about the sonde array. The salinity reads are steady, and the oysters already like the lines we put in. Looks like we have a viable cycle."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Good. Once the grant clears we can automate the sensors and start cross-checking yields with nutrient loads. If we open the data publicly, other towns upriver can adopt the same model."

    elias_jun "You always want the world to be a little more generous and a little less mysterious by the numbers."

    maya_reyes "I want the world to be survivable. That sounds less romantic in a thesis, but it's true."

    elias_jun "It's the most loving thing I've ever heard."

    "Maya Reyes (your hands stop moving for a second, soil under your nails like memory)" "We love by making things that let other people keep living here."

    elias_jun "So we make the things. And we keep making them. Together."
    "The months fold into each other: satellite calls with Ayla arranging permits and monitoring corridors; Rita organizing barter markets so Marisora craftspeople could sell their wares in the new town; Arlo taking a management course and"
    "then falling in love with a local oyster farmer. You send boxes back upriver — not just seeds, but memory-objects: a festival banner, a battered sign from the bakery, jars of preserved lemons."

    menu:
        "Send a small package of mangrove seedlings to Marisora every month.":
            "The seedlings arrive like postcards. People plant them in battered pots and along makeshift barriers. Photos come back with mud-smeared hands and stubborn smiles; the exchange becomes ritual."
        "Devote the monthly shipments to training materials and toolkits instead.":
            "Toolkits arrive: manuals, hand tools, spare sensors. The town's capacity grows in a different way — hands get steadier; the conversations at the Harbor change from grieving to planning."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue main narrative"

    "You learn to share chores across shifts and schedules — heeding the week's tide and each other's sleep. Some nights Elias works on a frame until late, leaving you a note folded under a jar" "Left you coffee. Be brave."
    "Ayla appears occasionally in person and more often in late-night video calls. Her crispness is the same, but her edges are softened by the fact that the plans worked — by the sight of functioning sensor"
    "networks and a community that is not merely surviving but beginning to archive the things it needs."
    show dr_ayla_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_ayla_voss "Your data looks promising. The regional board is considering scaling pilot funding. This model — your model — could be a template."

    maya_reyes "We can't erase what Marisora lost. But if other towns can adopt these modular systems early, maybe they won't have to choose like we did."

    dr_ayla_voss "I underestimate the value of localized knowledge. You and Elias taught me that."

    maya_reyes "And you taught us how to get the permits done."

    dr_ayla_voss "We all have roles."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Garden Above Your Rented Room | Sunset]
    hide elias_jun
    hide maya_reyes
    hide dr_ayla_voss

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft city murmurs, a distant bell, the rustle of leaves]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm cello and piano; the melody reaches a gentle peak]
    "Maya Reyes and Elias Jun sit on opposite sides of a low crate-turned-table, hands occupied with a routine that is now sacred: potting a new mangrove slip, checking a sensor's battery, sipping soup warmed from a"
    "thermos. Above you the sky bleeds the same colors as Marisora's dusk, as if all horizons share family genes."
    show elias_jun at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_jun "Do you ever picture the harbor? Not as it is now, but —"
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "I picture the harbor with more mangroves. I picture kids who never had to empty tidewater out of their lives because someone planted in time. I picture Rita painting a new board for the bakery, and Arlo leading a training session on oyster-line maintenance."

    elias_jun "I picture that too. I picture us old and grayer and still fixing something every week."

    maya_reyes "I sometimes picture sitting on the same rooftop, a hundred small roots tangled in the pots between us."

    elias_jun "Promise me something stupid and kind."

    maya_reyes "What?"

    elias_jun "That we'll keep sending ridiculous postcards to Marisora. That we'll keep the festival banner in the truck and never throw it out. Promise me that when the tide-watch finally stops ticking in a hundred years, someone will use it to anchor a childhood fort."

    "Maya Reyes (you press the tide-watch to your palm on the table)" "I promise. We'll keep the artifacts and the seeds and the songs. We'll build in the new place until it's full of the same stubborn love."
    "He reaches across the crate and takes your hand — not a dramatized clasp, but a firm, familiar grip. The contact is both tender and logistical: a human hinge."

    elias_jun "This is the rise, then. Not a clean fix but a long-making. We plant, we teach, we stitch, we grieve—"

    maya_reyes "—and we keep making room for one another while doing it."
    "There is a fullness in your chest that is not absence but an accumulation of purpose. Marisora will always be a bruise and a balm in the same place; leaving did not sever it. Instead, you"
    "learned to carry it more flexibly, to share its pieces where they could grow again."
    hide elias_jun
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The wind in the mangrove slips, a soft metallic creak from the telescope mount]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Strings resolve into a warm, settled chord]
    "You breathe, and the breath is steady. You have traded the rooftop watch for rented rooms with rooftop gardens, for modular aquaculture grids, for a new ledger of hard-won knowledge. The wounds of distance soften with"
    "parcels — seedlings shipped like love letters, small crates of preserved lemons and festival paints — and with visits that are crowded with work and laughter."
    "Rita visits, and she unpacks a box that smells of old bread and paint. She hugs you like a tide folding into a bay."
    show rita_ortega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rita_ortega "You ever regret it?"

    "Maya Reyes (it takes you half a second to answer, the honest one)" "Sometimes, for a moment. But then I see this — the seedlings, the kids learning to tie oyster-lines, Elias' ridiculous sketches becoming barges that actually float — and regret becomes a tool rather than a chain."

    rita_ortega "Good. Use it to keep building."
    "Elias Jun lifts his mug to you, a small ritual you've made for nights when the work feels endless."
    show elias_jun at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_jun "To making roots in new soil."
    show maya_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "To making roots."
    "You and Elias stand on the rooftop as the light finally thins into a blue that feels like a closing page. The river below turns like a slow thought. In the distance, Marisora's silhouette is a"
    "memory that hums in your bones — a harbor that taught you how to name loss and make plans anyway."
    "You set the tide-watch on the crate between you and Elias Jun and, for once, you both let your guard down. You are tired in a way that means you have done enough for tonight. The future waits with a busy, quiet patience."
    "You tuck a small mangrove slip into Elias Jun's coat pocket without ceremony. He slips it back to you later for safekeeping. The gesture is practical, affectionate, the way hands teach love."
    hide rita_ortega
    hide elias_jun
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Single, gentle violin line that resolves upward]
    "You know the road ahead will be long — long commutes, funding squeezes, nights of debate and repairing things with less than you wished you had. But you also know this: you and Elias, and the"
    "people you traveled with, have altered a shape of the map. You carried seeds across a stretch of water and planted protocols into municipal logic. You have built something that will let people choose differently."
    "You breathe again. The tide-watch ticks. The rooftop garden turns quiet as sleep claims the town."

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm strings sustain, then soften into silence]

    scene bg ch14_601bcb_9 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
